04133nam a22006135i 9780300157475DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20181983ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001574757 a10.12987/97803001574752doi  a(DE-B1597)486588  a(OCoLC)1024016340  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBS680.C45bL48 1993eb 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a220.6/4222  aBC 69202rvk1 aHuntington, Samuel P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Death and Resurrection of the Beloved Son /cSamuel P. Huntington. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1983  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPart I. A Father's Gift -- tPart II. The Beloved Sons in Genesis -- tPart III. The Beloved Son Between Zion and Golgotha -- tNotes -- tScripture Index -- tAuthor Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe near-sacrifice and miraculous restoration of a beloved son is a central but largely overlooked theme in both Judaism and Christianity, celebrated in biblical texts on Isaac, Ishmael, Jacob, Joseph, and Jesus. In this highly original book, Jon D. Levenson explores how this notion of child sacrifice constitutes an overlooked bond between the two religions.Levenson argues that although the practice of child sacrifice was eradicated during the late seventh and sixth centuries B.C.E, the idea of sacrificing the first-born son (or the late-born son whose preferential treatment promotes him to that exalted rank) remained potent in religious literature. Analyzing texts from the ancient Near East, the Hebrew Bible, the New Testament, and rabbinic literature, Levenson shows how tales of the son handed over to death by his loving father in the Hebrew Bible influenced the Church's identification of Jesus as sacrificial victim. According to Levenson, the transformation of the idea of child sacrifice was central to the accounts given by the people Israel and the early Church of their respective origins, and it also underlay the theologies of chosenness embraced, in their differing ways, by the two religions. Furthermore, the longstanding claim of the Church that it supersedes the Jews, says Levenson, both continues and transforms elements of the old narrative pattern in which a late-born son dislodges his first-born brothers. Levenson's book, which offers novel interpretations of several areas crucial to biblical studies, will be essential reading for scholars in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChild sacrifice in the Bible. 0aChild sacrificexChristianity. 0aChild sacrificexJudaism. 0aChildrenxDeathxReligious aspects. 0aJudaismxDoctrines. 0aResurrection. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030005532040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015747540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157475/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY